> With a subtly nutty flavour from the creamy cashew sauce and the beautifully fragrant pilau rice, this is an exciting twist on a familiar dish that the whole house is going to love.

Place a medium #pot over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Add the @rice{150%g} and @ground turmeric{1%sachet} and fry for ~{2-3%mins}.

Add @water{300%ml} (double for 4p) and @vegetable stock{1%sachet} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%mins}, then remove the pot from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%mins} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Place a large #pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the oil is hot, add the @diced Irish chicken breast{260%g} and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Fry until golden brown on the outside, ~{5-7%mins}.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(halved and chopped) into small pieces.

Add the onion to the chicken and fry for ~{3-4%mins}.

Blend the @cashews{20%g} and @cream{250%g} in a #food processor until almost smooth (be careful not to overwhip the cream).

Add the @North Indian style spice mix{1%sachet} to the chicken and cook for ~{1%min}.

Pour in the @passata{1%pack} and creamy cashew mixture and allow to cook for ~{5-7%mins}.

Season to taste with salt, pepper and @sugar{to taste}.

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all).

Fluff up the pilau with a #fork and serve alongside the curry.

Top with a sprinkling of coriander.